- **2) Why Docker? Problem statement vs Virtual Machines (VMs)**
  - VM characteristics discussed:
    - Full OS per VM, requires heavy hardware, larger disk footprint (example: VM images 10–30+ GB with apps/logs).
    - Advantages: multiple OS on one host, snapshots, easier testing across OS flavors, cost saving vs physical machines, faster provisioning vs buying hardware.
    - Disadvantages: heavy size, slower transport/collaboration, single point of failure on hypervisor, scaling overhead.
  - Docker/container benefits:
    - Lightweight images, portable, consistent runtime (pack binaries + libs + config), faster distribution, better for microservices.
    - Use-case: microservice architectures (front-end, product-catalog, payment, auth run as separate containers).

- **3) Core Docker concepts explained**
  - Image: packaged artifact containing binaries, libraries, OS layers relevant to the app.
  - Container: a running instance of an image (runtime). "Image becomes container when run."
  - Dockerfile: text blueprint to build images (keywords: FROM, RUN, COPY, ADD, WORKDIR, CMD, ENTRYPOINT, EXPOSE, MAINTAINER (deprecated), ENV, VOLUME, USER).
  - Registry / Docker Hub: public registry hosting millions of images (official vs community images; verified images have blue tick).
  - Docker daemon (dockerd), Docker client (CLI), Docker Hub — architecture flow: client -> daemon -> local images -> if not found -> Docker Hub -> daemon pulls -> daemon creates container -> streams output to client.

- **4) Image tags, sizes and common base images**
  - Tag concept: name:tag (e.g., ubuntu:22.04, hello-world:latest).
  - Size examples from demo:
    - ubuntu image: larger (multiple MBs/GB depending on flavor/tag)
    - centos example: larger (~300 MB referenced)
    - alpine: minimal (often ~5–15 MB depending on tag); very commonly used as small base image
  - Practical note: choose official/verified images in production; check last-updated and security maintenance.

- **5) Docker lifecycle & commands (demonstrated)**
